8. Key flows to prototype
Flow 1: Participant discovers through community adjacency
User opens Home
Sees activity map and relevant communities
Notices hotspot tied to CI + another overlapping scene
Opens event
Sees “suggested by your CI community” / “people from your circle are going”
Opens linked facilitator or community
Saves or marks attending

This is one of the main conceptual flows.

Flow 2: Newcomer to city
User enters city
Sees communities rather than just isolated events
Opens a community
Reads “how to engage”
Finds beginner-friendly upcoming offering
Joins event

This validates legibility and entry.

Flow 3: Community steward sees opportunity
Steward opens pulse dashboard
Sees rising participation overlap with another community
Sees suggested event relevant to their members
Approves / features it
Updates community page or upcoming rhythm

This validates “opportunity, not roster.”

Flow 4: Facilitator publishes once, shares across communities
Facilitator creates event
Links their own profile
Selects two or three relevant communities
Publishes
Event appears:
on their profile
in explore
in suggested queue for communities
Participant later discovers it through community context

This is a key differentiator.

Flow 5: Member suggests event to community
Participant sees event
Clicks “Suggest to community”
Chooses one of their communities
Adds a short note
Community steward later sees it in queue

This is directly tied to your workshop-circle reflection.

